<deserialization_vulnerability_guide>
<title>INSECURE DESERIALIZATION</title>

<critical>Insecure deserialization occurs when untrusted data is used to instantiate objects without proper validation. Attackers can manipulate serialized data to execute arbitrary code, bypass authentication, or perform denial of service attacks. This vulnerability class consistently leads to remote code execution.</critical>

<scope>
- Java: ObjectInputStream, XMLDecoder, XStream, Jackson, SnakeYAML
- PHP: unserialize(), phar://, __wakeup(), __destruct()
- Python: pickle, PyYAML, marshal, shelve
- .NET: BinaryFormatter, DataContractSerializer, JSON.NET, XmlSerializer
- Ruby: Marshal.load, YAML.load
- Node.js: node-serialize, serialize-javascript
</scope>

<methodology>
1. Identify deserialization sinks: endpoints accepting serialized data, file uploads, cookies, hidden fields.
2. Determine serialization format through magic bytes, content types, or error messages.
3. Map available classes/gadgets in the application's classpath or dependencies.
4. Construct gadget chains that lead from deserialization to code execution.
5. Deliver payload via identified input vector and confirm exploitation.
</methodology>

<detection_methods>
<magic_bytes>
{% raw %}
# Java serialized objects
AC ED 00 05 (0xaced0005) - Java ObjectInputStream
rO0 - Base64 encoded Java serialized object

# Python pickle
80 04 95 - Protocol 4
80 03 - Protocol 3
(dp0 - Protocol 0 (text-based)

# PHP serialized objects
O:4:"User":2:{s:8:"username";s:5:"admin";s:8:"password";s:6:"secret";}
a: - Array, O: - Object, s: - String, i: - Integer

# .NET BinaryFormatter
00 01 00 00 00 FF FF FF FF - BinaryFormatter magic

# Ruby Marshal
04 08 - Marshal.dump magic bytes
{% endraw %}
</magic_bytes>

<content_types>
- application/x-java-serialized-object
- application/x-java-object
- application/octet-stream (often used for binary serialization)
- application/x-httpd-php-serialized
- Content-Type headers may not be reliable; check body patterns
</content_types>

<indicators>
- Base64-encoded data in cookies, parameters, or hidden fields
- Binary data in request/response bodies
- Java exceptions: java.io.InvalidClassException, ClassNotFoundException
- PHP errors: unserialize() warning, __wakeup failed
- .NET errors: SerializationException, TypeLoadException
</indicators>
</detection_methods>

